cmCourseInfo.description: Principles and concepts of evolution and ecology related to origins of adaptation and biodiversity. Mechanisms and processes driving biological diversification illustrated from various perspectives using empirical and theoretical approaches. Topics include: genetic diversity, natural selection, speciation, physiological, population, and community ecology, maintenance of species diversity, conservation, species extinction, global environmental change, and invasion biology. A lab coat is required and the cost is approximately $16 if students wish to purchase it through the Department. (Lab Materials Fee: $25)
cmCourseInfo.title: Adaptation and Biodiversity
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: Grade 12 Biology or equivalent. Students without high school Biology must consult the BIO120 Office (bio120@utoronto.ca)

breadthTypes.description: BR=4 Living Things and Their Environment

notes.name: Course Note
notes.content:
Timetable Instructions
Optional weekly tutorials are offered W9 a.m. to allow students the opportunity to ask their professors questions, so keep this time available. Practicals (labs) meet in alternate weeks: practical meeting section numbers that end with 1 start the week of September 17; practical meeting section numbers that end with 2 start the week of September 24. Enrolment for a practical section is done on ACORN until the evening of Thursday September 6. As of September 11, laboratory enrolment and changes can ONLY be done by the BIO120H1 office; see the course site on Quercus for details (www.q.utoronto.ca). Do not remove yourself from a practical section on ACORN from September 7-10. Each student's laboratory week (1 or 2), day and room number will be posted after 5 p.m. on Monday, September 10 on Quercus. For your BIO120H1F laboratory, if you plan to take a CHM135H1F/136H1F laboratory on the same day in alternating weeks, select P sections IN BOTH COURSES that end in DIFFERENT digits (e.g.: P0301 in BIO120H1F and P0302 in CHM135H1F/136H1F). You CANNOT alternate labs in BIO120H1F on the same day as labs in CHM151Y1 or PHY131H1F/132H1F/151H1F.

cmCourseInfo.description: One of the goals of modern biology is to understand how the basic building blocks of life give rise to biological form and function. This course provides students with a common lexicon to understand the key principles and concepts in molecular and cell biology, with a focus on how the building blocks of life lead to functioning cells. (Lab Materials Fee: $10). Lab coat and safety glasses are required for use in laboratories; students are responsible for purchasing these items (approximate cost is $25).
cmCourseInfo.title: Molecular and Cell Biology
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: SBI4U and SCH4U (Grade 12 University Preparation Biology and Chemistry) or permission of department. Please contact bio130@utoronto.ca for more information.

Laboratory sections (PRA) meet in alternate weeks: practical meeting section numbers that end with 1 will take place in the weeks of: January 14th, January 28th, February 11th, March 4th and March 18th. Practical meeting section numbers that end with 2 will take place in the weeks of: January 21st, February 4th, February 25th, March 11th, and March 25th. Please refer the BIO130 description at http://csb.utoronto.ca/undergraduate-studies/undergraduate-courses/undergraduate-course-level-100/ for more information on alternating labs. Laboratory enrolment can be done on ACORN until Monday, January 7th. cmCourseInfo.description: Dynamics of genetic and ecological change in biological systems, from genomes to ecosystems. Evolutionary genetic and ecological perspectives on wide-ranging topics including disease, aging, sexual conflict, genetics of human differences, conservation, and global climate change. Applications of evolutionary, ecological, and molecular-genetic principles and processes. Responsibilities of human societies in a changing world. (Lab Materials Fee: $25).
cmCourseInfo.title: From Genomes to Ecosystems in a Changing World

cmCourseInfo.description: The genome is the "book of life," providing instructions to construct an organism. This course introduces genome biology and explores how the building blocks of life are networked into functioning organisms. We will investigate how cells perceive internal and external cues, how gene expression is shaped by this perception, and how these events give rise to tissues, organs, and whole organisms. (Lab Materials Fee: $20). Lab coat and safety glasses are required for use in laboratories; students are responsible for purchasing these items (approximate cost is $25).
cmCourseInfo.title: From Genes to Organisms
cmCourseInfo.exclusionsText: BIO240H1, BIO241H1, BIO250Y1, BIO255H1, BIO255Y1. Students who have only completed one of BIO240H1 or BIO241H1 can take BIO230H1 for credit.

cmCourseInfo.description: Introduction to structure, function, and ecology of vegetative and reproductive processes in plants with a focus on flowering plants and gymnosperms. Lectures and labs emphasize photosynthesis, respiration, mineral nutrition, transport processes, patterns of plant growth and development, the role of hormones in development, photomorphogenesis, and plant reproduction. (Lab Materials Fee: $25).

cmCourseInfo.description: The genome is the "book of life," providing instructions to construct an organism. This course introduces genome biology and explores how the building blocks of life are networked into functioning organisms. We will investigate how cells perceive internal and external cues, how gene expression is shaped by this perception, and how these events give rise to tissues, organs, and whole organisms. The Enhanced Laboratory provides the opportunity for greater laboratory skill development in modern investigative techniques and is intended for students interested in conducting their own laboratory research. (Lab Materials Fee: $50).
